    <li>
        Explanation
        <div>
            <p>
                You should first execute the Login-AzureRmAccount cmdlet. This is because the rest of the script is clearly dependent on Azure resource manager cmdlets, and Add-AzureAccount will only support the older Azure service management capability.
            </p>
            <p>
                You should use the New-AzureResourceGroup cmdlet and not New-AzureResourceGroupDeployment. New-AzureResourceGroup actually creates a new resource group in Azure, whereas New-AzureResourceGroupDeployment will deploy a set of resources to an existing resource group in Azure.
            </p>
            <p>
                Next, you need to provide the parameter to indicate the type of storage requested. You need to provide read/write geo replicated storage, and this can only be identified as th");
            WriteLiteral(@"e SkuName of the storage type. The use of -kind indicates the newer V2 storage types, but that parameter does not allow the entry of the storage access type or replication strategy.
            </p>
            <p>
                Next, you need to provide the SkuName of the storage type. You should use Standard_GRS. GRS represents Geo Replicated Storage and is read/write in nature. Standard_LRS is Local Replicated Storage only, and Standard_RAGRS is Geo Replicated but in Read Access mode only, so neither meets the requirements.
            </p>
            <p>
                Then you need to request the Access Keys for the newly created storage account. You should use Get-AzureStorageAccountKey because this requests the key for the storage account.  Get- AzureRmStorage will get context for the Storage Account itself, but not the access keys. The access keys could be derived from the Storage Context, but not without additional script content. You should not use Get-AzureKeyVault because this cmdlet get");
            WriteLiteral(@"s the context of an AzureKeyVault, which is used for multiple reasons but predominantly for providing secure storage of secrets and credentials.
            </p>
        </div>
